<div class="content">

  <h1>Simple Java Mail Modules</h1>

  <section>
    <p class="wide">
      Simple Java Mail core features can be used without any external libraries, but you can add some features by
      depending on additional modules, which bring in some additional dependencies of their own.
    </p>
  </section>
  <section>
    <div class="view">
      <p>
        The Core Module is included by default when you add Simple Java Mail. The other modules from the implementation layer can be
        added to complement Simple Java Mail.
      </p>
      <p>
        On the other hand, if you depend on one of the integration modules, you get Simple Java Mail automatically as well. Again you
      can add the other modules from the implementation layer to complement Simple Java Mail.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="side">
      <img src="../../assets/module_architecture.png">
    </div>
  </section>

  <h2 id="batch-module">Batch and Clustering support</h2>

  <section>
    <p>
      To enable support for async / batch mode sending and clustering (see <a href="configuration.html#section-batch-and-clustering">Configuration</a>), include the following library:
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-xml">&lt;dependency&gt;
    &lt;groupId&gt;org.simplejavamail&lt;/groupId&gt;
    &lt;artifactId&gt;batch-module&lt;/artifactId&gt;
&lt;/dependency&gt;</code></pre>
    <p>
      This adds the following 3rd party dependencies:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><a class="indent" href="https://github.com/simple-java-mail/smtp-connection-pool">simple-java-mail:smtp-connection-pool</a></li>
    </ul>
    This allows you to send emails asynchronous with configuration options for thread management and SMTP connection
    pooling. See <a href="configuration.html#section-batch-support">configuration</a> for more details.
  </section>

  <h2 id="authenticated-socks-module">Authenticated (SOCKS) proxy support</h2>

  <section>
    <p>
      To enable support for authenticated SOCKS proxy servers (see <a href="features.html#section-proxy">Features</a>),
      include the following library:
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-xml">&lt;dependency&gt;
    &lt;groupId&gt;org.simplejavamail&lt;/groupId&gt;
    &lt;artifactId&gt;authenticated-socks-module&lt;/artifactId&gt;
&lt;/dependency&gt;</code></pre>
    <p>
      This adds no additional 3rd party dependencies.
    </p>
  </section>

  <h2 id="outlook-module">Outlook support</h2>

  <section>
    <p>
      To enable support for parsing Outlook messages (see <a href="features.html#section-generate-converting">Features</a>),
      include the following library:
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-xml">&lt;dependency&gt;
    &lt;groupId&gt;org.simplejavamail&lt;/groupId&gt;
    &lt;artifactId&gt;outlook-module&lt;/artifactId&gt;
&lt;/dependency&gt;</code></pre>
    <p>
      This adds the following 3rd party dependencies:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><a class="indent" href="https://github.com/bbottema/outlook-message-parser">org.simplejavamail:outlook-message-parser</a></li>
      <li>Which in turn adds:</li>
      <li><a class="indent" href="https://poi.apache.org">org.apache.poi:poi</a></li>
      <li><a class="indent" href="https://poi.apache.org">org.apache.poi:poi-scratchpad</a></li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <h2 id="dkim-module">DKIM support</h2>

  <section>
    <p>
      To enable support for DKIM signing (see <a href="features.html#section-dkim">Features</a>),
      include the following library:
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-xml">&lt;dependency&gt;
    &lt;groupId&gt;org.simplejavamail&lt;/groupId&gt;
    &lt;artifactId&gt;dkim-module&lt;/artifactId&gt;
&lt;/dependency&gt;</code></pre>
    <p>
      This adds the following 3rd party dependencies:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><a class="indent" href="https://github.com/markenwerk/java-utils-mail-dkim">net.markenwerk:utils-mail-dkim</a></li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <h2 id="smime-module">S/MIME support</h2>

  <section>
    <p>
      To enable support for reading <a href="https://docs.ipswitch.com/moveit/central/onlineguide/en/MICSMIMEEmailOverview.htm">S/MIME</a>
      signed / encrypted email, (see <a href="features.html#section-smime">Features</a>),
      include the following library:
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-xml">&lt;dependency&gt;
    &lt;groupId&gt;org.simplejavamail&lt;/groupId&gt;
    &lt;artifactId&gt;smime-module&lt;/artifactId&gt;
&lt;/dependency&gt;</code></pre>
    <p>
      This adds the following 3rd party dependencies:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><a class="indent" href="https://github.com/markenwerk/java-utils-mail-smime">net.markenwerk:utils-mail-smime</a></li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <h2 id="cli-module">CLI support</h2>

  <section>
    <p>
        To enable CLI support (see <a href="cli.html#navigation">CLI</a>), include the following module:
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-xml">&lt;dependency&gt;
    &lt;groupId&gt;org.simplejavamail&lt;/groupId&gt;
    &lt;artifactId&gt;cli-module&lt;/artifactId&gt;
&lt;/dependency&gt;</code></pre>
    <p>
      This adds the following 3rd party dependencies:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><a class="indent" href="https://github.com/remkop/picocli">info.picocli:picocli</a></li>
      <li><a class="indent" href="https://github.com/dnault/therapi-runtime-javadoc">com.github.therapi:therapi-runtime-javadoc</a></li>
    </ul>
    <p class="wide">
      <strong>Note:</strong> Simple Java Mail core has a 'provided' dependency on <em>com.github.therapi:therapi-runtime-javadoc-scribe</em>
      which burns Javadoc into Simple Java Mail at compile time. This cannot be made optional. If this is a real concern, an option
      could be to provide two versions of Simple Java Mail: one with embedded Javadoc and one without (incompatible with the Cli Module).
      This is currently not in scope.
    </p>
  </section>

  <h2 id="spring-module">Spring support</h2>

  <section>
    <p>
      To enable support for Spring (see <a href="configuration.html#section-spring-support">Configuration</a>),
      make sure the following libraries can be found on the classpath (in most cases will be there anyway):
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-xml">&lt;dependency&gt;
    &lt;groupId&gt;org.simplejavamail&lt;/groupId&gt;
    &lt;artifactId&gt;spring-module&lt;/artifactId&gt;
&lt;/dependency&gt;</code></pre>
    <p>
      This adds the Spring core dependency, which is assumed to be on the classpath already.
    </p>
  </section>

